\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 18. P. strobus} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 1001 (1753). Tree up to 50 m; crown pyramidal at first, later becoming broader; bark greyish-green and smooth on young trees, becoming brown and fissured on old trees. Twigs becoming glabrous, or remaining pubescent below leaf-traces. Leaves 5-14 cm, slender, flexible, patent. Cone 8-20 × 3-4 cm, cylindrical, often curved near the apex, pendent. Seeds 5-8 mm; wing 18-25 mm.{\i  Planted for timber, especialy in C. Europe.} [Au Be Bu Cz Da Ga Ge He It Po Rm Rs(C) Su Tu.] ({\i E. & C. North America}.)
