\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. S. sempervirens} (D. Don) Endl., {\i Syn. Conif.} 198 (1847). Up to 100 m, often suckering freely from the base, trunk 3-4·5 m in diameter; outer bark thick, exfoliating in dark brown plates, revealing the inner, bright red bark. Leaves of lateral twigs 6-25 × 2-3 mm, acute, often falcate, dark green above; leaves of leading and cone-bearing twigs 6 mm, incurved and with a sharp callose point at the apex, decurrent at the base. Female cone 18-25 × 12 mm, ovoid; scales expanded into a rhomboidal disc, rarely with a mucro. Seeds 3-5 on each scale.{\i  Planted for ornament and occasionally for timber.} [Ba Ga It.] ({\i W. North America.})
\par

