\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 1. S. giganteum} (Lindley) Buchholz,{\i  Amer. Jour. Bot. }{\b 26:} 536 (1939) ({\i Seqoia gigantea} Decne, non Endl., {\i S. wellingtonia} Seem.). Up to 80 m, with narrow pyramidal crown; trunk up to 7 m in diameter above the thickened, buttressed base; bark thick and spongy, reddish-brown. Leaves c. 1 cm, becoming longer on older twigs, ovate to lanceolate, flat above, convex beneath, broadly decurrent at the base. Female cone 3-5(-8) × 2-3·5(-4·5) cm, terminal, ovoid; scales expanded into a rhomboidal disc, with a depression in the middle often bearing a slender mucro. Seeds 3-7 on each scale.{\i  Planted for ornament and occasionally for timber.} [Au Ga.] ({\i California}.)
\par

